[2026-05-26] #idea
Starting point: particle simulation in vanilla JS + Canvas. No frameworks, no
physics libraries. The interesting code is the physics — using a library would
give away the point.

[2026-05-26] #decision
Canvas 2D over WebGL. Performance is not the goal here — understanding the
simulation loop and numerical methods is.

[2026-05-26] #decision
Start with Euler integration. It's the simplest possible integrator and it will
visibly break under certain conditions (large timesteps, fast collisions). That
breakdown is informative — it motivates improving the method rather than
understanding the improvement in the abstract.

[2026-05-26] #decision
Separate logic from rendering from the start. The integrator lives in
web/lib/Physics.mjs and knows nothing about Canvas. The renderer in
web/apps/physics/ consumes it. This keeps the physics testable in Node.

[2026-05-26] #decision
Write Vec2 from scratch. A linear algebra library would remove the interesting
parts of implementing a physics sim. Vec2 is small enough to own completely.

[2026-05-26] #question
What integration methods exist beyond Euler? When does Euler visibly fail —
what will we observe? Candidates to explore later: Verlet, RK4, symplectic
Euler. Each has different energy conservation properties.

[2026-05-26] #idea
Intended progression: static ball → moving → bouncing → two bodies →
configurable dt → stress test → observe breakdown → improve. Each step is
a working state. Nothing skipped.

[2026-05-26] #observation
This problem may have computationally irreducible regions — particularly once
multiple bodies interact. No amount of planning will predict what emerges.
The simulation has to run.

[2026-05-26] #question
At what point does this become an n-body problem? Two balls bouncing is
trivial. Ten? A hundred? Where does interesting emergent behaviour appear?

[2026-05-26] #idea
Candidates noted for later: rigid bodies (rotation, torque, collision response),
soft bodies / cloth (spring networks), orbital / n-body (gravity wells, chaos),
fluid (Navier-Stokes — hardest, deferred). These are not goals — they are
possible destinations depending on what the simulation reveals.
